snippet: Leaders of the movement said they had moved the needle, however slightly, toward the possibility of a more democratic future for Hong Kong.
abstract: Organizers of pro-democracy protests in Hong Kong say they have moved the needle toward more democratic future as protests dwindle and life returns to its normal routine; there is sense that after 11 days of street protests that movement has experienced dissipation of energy, despite insistence on part of organizers that movement is long-term project.

byline.original: By MICHAEL FORSYTHE and ALAN WONG
byline.contributor: Reporting was contributed by Chris Buckley, Keith Bradsher, Austin Ramzy and Edward Wong in Hong Kong, and research by Kiki Zhao in Beijing.

lead_paragraph: Leaders of the movement said they had moved the needle, however slightly, toward the possibility of a more democratic future for Hong Kong.

headline.main: Protest Organizers Claim Progress for Hong Kong
headline.print_headline: Protest Organizers Claim Progress for Hong Kong
